Looking at the mutation, the original code is:
```javascript
if (totalTimezones !== memoizedTimezones) Object.keys(data.timezones).forEach(getTimezone);
```

The mutated code is:
```javascript
if (true) Object.keys(data.timezones).forEach(getTimezone);
```

The key difference is that the original code only re-memoizes timezones when `totalTimezones !== memoizedTimezones`, while the mutated code always does it (every call to `getAllTimezones`).

Looking at `memoizeTimezone`:
```javascript
function memoizeTimezone(timezone) {
  if (!timezone) return;
  timezones[timezone.name] = timezone;
  memoizedTimezones = Object.keys(timezone).length;  // Sets to number of keys in timezone object, not total count
}
```

After the first call to `getAllTimezones`, `memoizedTimezones` will be set to the number of keys in a timezone object (not `totalTimezones`). So in the original code, subsequent calls would check `totalTimezones !== memoizedTimezones` - since `memoizedTimezones` would be something like 5 (keys in a timezone object) and `totalTimezones` is the total number of timezones (much larger), the condition would be `true` on every call too!

